7. Compute the average delay by destination, then join on the airports data frame so you can show the spatial distribution of delays. Hereâs an easy way to draw a map of the United States:

avg_delay <- flights %>%
  group_by(dest) %>%
  summarise(mean_arr_delay = mean(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE),

  theme_minimal()

1. Can you explain whatâs happening with the keys in this equi join? Why are they different?

When there is no âkeep=trueâ the join will merge the keys into one column but when there is âkeep=trueâ then the keys will be in seperate columns.

Code 
x |> full_join(y, join_by(key == key))
# A tibble: 4 Ã 3
    key val_x val_y
  <dbl> <chr> <chr>
1     1 x1    y1   
2     2 x2    y2   
3     3 x3    <NA> 
4     4 <NA>  y3

2. When finding if any party period overlapped with another party period we used q < q in the join_by()? Why? What happens if you remove this inequality?

The âq < qâ is used so that there is no duplicate pairs and also no self matches. If you remove the youâre code output could have duplicate pairs and self matches.
